│ at the end of the object. The `ConstantStruct` handler at line 472 uses `getElementContainingOffset` to find the starting    │
│ element. If this returns an element for an out-of-bounds offset, the subsequent relative offset calculation can be wrong,    │
│ leading to the faulty recursive call.                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ A robust solution is to prevent the recursive call if the relative offset is out of bounds for the target element. The       │
│ current check `if (ByteOffset < EltSize && !ReadDataFromGlobal(...))` is insufficient because the local `ByteOffset` can be  │
│ wrong.                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ I will add a check that validates the *absolute* offset against the element's bounds before attempting the recursive call.   │
│ Inside the `ConstantStruct` handler's loop, before the recursive call at line 484, I will add a check: `if (CurEltOffset +   │
│ ByteOffset >= SL->getSizeInBytes()) continue;`. This ensures that the absolute access position (`CurEltOffset + ByteOffset`) │
│ is within the struct's bounds. If not, we skip to the next element, which will correctly terminate the loop. This prevents   │
│ the invalid recursive call without altering assertions or relying on a single entry-point guard.                             │
